Angular has undergone a massive renaissance. While features like standalone components and hydration changed how we structure our applications, the introduction of Signals fundamentally changed how we think about reactivity.
For years, RxJS was the unquestioned king of data flow in Angular. If you wanted a variable to be reactive, you wrapped it in a BehaviorSubject, piped it through operators, and unwrapped it using the async pipe.
But with Signals now fully mature, many teams face an architectural dilemma: Should we completely rewrite our data layers to remove RxJS, or are we throwing the baby out with the bathwater?
Let’s break down exactly when to use Signals, when to stick with RxJS, and how to make them coexist seamlessly.
1. The Core Philosophy: Pull vs. Push
To make the right architectural decisions, we have to look past syntax and understand the core behavioral differences:
RxJS is a Push-Based Stream
RxJS is built around events happening over time. A stream doesn’t care about the past or the future; it notifies consumers when a new piece of data passes through the pipeline. It is perfect for handling asynchronous, event-driven operations.
Signals are Synchronous State
Signals are built around values that exist right now. They represent a cell of data that is always readable synchronously via mySignal(). When the value changes, dependent computations and the UI update automatically.
Key Rule of Thumb: If you are managing state (the current value of a counter, user details, toggle states), use Signals. If you are managing events (button clicks, WebSocket messages, HTTP responses over time), use RxJS.
2. When to Use Signals (The New Defaults)
For 90% of your component-level reactivity and local state management, Signals should be your default choice.
Local Component State
Instead of managing multiple local primitives or complex RxJS subjects for local UI toggles, Signals keep things simple, readable, and highly performant.
@Component({
selector: 'app-user-profile',
standalone: true,
template: `
<div>
<h3>{{ fullName() }}</h3>
<button (click)="toggleEdit()">Edit Mode: {{ isEditing() ? 'ON' : 'OFF' }}</button>
</div>
`
})
export class UserProfileComponent {
// Simple Read/Write State
isEditing = signal(false);
firstName = signal('John');
lastName = signal('Doe'); // Derived State (Automatically caches and updates!)
fullName = computed(() => `${this.firstName()} ${this.lastName()}`);
toggleEdit() {
this.isEditing.update(value => !value);
}
}

• No Memory Leaks: Signals don’t require subscriptions. You never have to worry about takeUntil() or ngOnDestroy.

• Glitch-Free Execution: The computed values evaluate lazily and avoid intermediate dirty states—a notorious headache in complex RxJS combinations.
3. When RxJS is Still Unbeatable
Do not delete @angular/core/rxjs-interop just yet. Signals are synchronous, meaning they cannot replace RxJS when handling time-sensitive or asynchronous processes.
Race Conditions and Switching Streams
If you have a search input where typing too fast can cause race conditions, RxJS operators like switchMap, debounceTime, and distinctUntilChanged remain elite.
// Signals cannot easily replicate this complex async orchestration natively
this.searchResults$ = this.searchControl.valueChanges.pipe(
debounceTime(300),
distinctUntilChanged(),
switchMap(query => this.apiService.search(query))
);Complex Event Orchestration
If you need to wait for three separate WebSockets to emit a specific sequence before triggering a modal, zip, forkJoin, or combineLatest from RxJS will get the job done in five lines of code. Trying to replicate this logic purely in Signals will result in messy state machines.
4. The Perfect Coexistence: RxJS Interop
The magic happens when you treat Signals and RxJS as partners rather than rivals. Angular provides standard utilities to bridge both worlds.
import { toSignal, toObservable } from '@angular/core/rxjs-interop';@Component({ ... })
export class ProductDashboardComponent {
private productService = inject(ProductService);
// 1. Handle the async event stream using RxJS
searchQuery$ = new BehaviorSubject<string>('');
products$ = this.searchQuery$.pipe(
debounceTime(400),
switchMap(query => this.productService.getProducts(query))
);
// 2. Convert it to a Signal for clean template rendering
products = toSignal(this.products$, { initialValue: [] });
// Now, 'products()' can be consumed cleanly, bypassing the async pipe entirely!
}
Summary Checklist for Modern Angular Architecture
Scenario Use Signals?Use RxJS?Template Binding / Local UI State Yes (Fast & clean) No Derived Synchronous State (computed)Yes No HTTP Requests (Single fetch) Yes (Via Interop toSignal)Internally via HttpClientReal-time Data Streams (WebSockets) No Yes User Input Debouncing / Typeahead No Yes
Conclusion
The architecture of modern Angular isn’t about choosing Signals OR RxJS — it’s about leveraging Signals AND RxJS.
By offloading your local data states, derived properties, and template bindings to Signals, you dramatically clean up your components. By reserving RxJS for complex asynchronous flows, you maintain the robust enterprise-grade stream management that makes Angular so powerful in the first place.
What are your thoughts on migrating to a Signal-first architecture? Let me know in the comments below! If you found this guide helpful, don’t forget to leave some claps 👏.
